PUH-BrianMartell The paper (arXiv:2508.20157, submitted August 2025, Anand et al.) reports the discovery of “Cloud-9” — a compact, isolated, starless H I cloud detected by FAST (Five-hundred-meter Aperture Spherical Telescope). Key findings: •  Mass ~10^4 M⊙, size ~30 pc, very high central density (~100 cm⁻³). •  No optical/IR counterpart — truly starless, no young stars, no dust. •  Kinematics suggest it’s not bound to any known galaxy, possibly a “RELHIC” (Relic H I Cloud) — primordial gas that never formed stars. •  Located ~500 kpc projected from M31, possibly in Local Group intergalactic medium. Relation to PUH v25 Strong mechanical alignment — Cloud-9 as a lattice-depleted relic zone. In PUH: •  Normal gas clouds have sufficient lattice tension/jitter to seed knot formation (stars). •  Cloud-9: Region where rebound shell fragmentation or throat backwash left depleted lattice — low ξ tension, no heavy cores to trigger collapse.
